# Plan: Extract Service Layer from Express Route Handlers

## Context

`src/routes/products.ts` and `src/routes/orders.ts` mix HTTP concerns (parsing
request params, sending responses) with business logic (filtering, validation,
calculations, state-machine transitions). This coupling makes the code hard to
unit-test and maintain. The goal is to extract all business logic into dedicated
service files while keeping route handlers thin (parse → call service → respond).

---

## Files to Create

- `src/services/product-service.ts`
- `src/services/order-service.ts`

## Files to Modify

- `src/routes/products.ts`
- `src/routes/orders.ts`

## Files Left Unchanged

- `src/app.ts`, `src/data.ts`, `src/types.ts`, `tests/products.test.ts`,
  `tests/orders.test.ts` — no changes needed.

---

## Step 1 — Create `src/services/product-service.ts`

### Local types (defined in this file)

```ts
interface ProductFilters {
  category?: string;
  minPrice?: number;
  maxPrice?: number;
}

interface ProductWithDetails extends Product {
  isLowStock: boolean;
  inventoryValue: number;
}

interface ProductListResult {
  products: Product[];
  summary: { count: number; totalInventoryValue: number; averagePrice: number };
}

type AdjustStockResult =
  | { success: true; product: ProductWithDetails }
  | { success: false; error: string; statusCode: 400 | 404 };
```

### Functions to implement

| Function | Logic extracted from route |
|---|---|
| `listProducts(filters: ProductFilters): ProductListResult` | Filtering by category/minPrice/maxPrice; summary calculation (totalInventoryValue, averagePrice) |
| `getProductById(id: number): ProductWithDetails \| null` | Lookup by id; compute `isLowStock` (stock < 10) and `inventoryValue` |
| `adjustProductStock(id: number, adjustment: unknown): AdjustStockResult` | Type-check adjustment, validate non-negative result, mutate `product.stock`, return enriched product |

### Imports

```ts
import { products } from "../data.js";
import type { Product } from "../types.js";
```

---

## Step 2 — Create `src/services/order-service.ts`

### Local types (defined in this file)

```ts
interface OrderFilters {
  userId?: number;
  status?: string;
}

interface EnrichedOrderItem extends OrderItem {
  productName: string;
}

interface EnrichedOrder extends Omit<Order, "items"> {
  items: EnrichedOrderItem[];
}

interface OrderListResult {
  orders: Order[];
  summary: { count: number; totalRevenue: number };
}

type CreateOrderResult =
  | { success: true; order: Order }
  | { success: false; error: string; statusCode: 400 };

type UpdateStatusResult =
  | { success: true; order: Order }
  | { success: false; error: string; statusCode: 400 | 404 };
```

### Functions to implement

| Function | Logic extracted from route |
|---|---|
| `listOrders(filters: OrderFilters): OrderListResult` | Filter by userId/status; calculate totalRevenue |
| `getOrderById(id: number): EnrichedOrder \| null` | Lookup by id; enrich items with `productName` from products array |
| `createOrder(input: unknown): CreateOrderResult` | All validation (userId/items required, non-empty, product exists, positive qty, stock check), stock deduction, order assembly, push to orders array |
| `updateOrderStatus(id: number, status: unknown): UpdateStatusResult` | Lookup, validate status string, enforce state-machine transitions, mutate order.status |

### Imports

```ts
import { orders, products, getNextOrderId } from "../data.js";
import type { Order, OrderItem, CreateOrderInput } from "../types.js";
```

---

## Step 3 — Refactor `src/routes/products.ts`

Replace the three handler bodies with thin wrappers:

```ts
import { listProducts, getProductById, adjustProductStock } from "../services/product-service.js";

// GET /products
router.get("/products", (req, res) => {
  const { category, minPrice, maxPrice } = req.query;
